900629-0157.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology &amp; Science:
   Apple Computer, in a Switch, Decides
   It Will Keep Claris Unit in Company
   ----
   By G. Pascal Zachary
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS AAPL LOTS
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
SOFTWARE (SOF)
</IN>
<LP>
   Apple Computer Inc. decided to fold its Claris software
unit -- which has spent most of this year laying plans for an
initial public offering -- back into the company.
   The move is a major switch for Apple, which formed Claris
three years ago to take over much of its personal-computer
software business. At the time, John Sculley, Apple's chief
executive officer, explained that Apple needed to distance
itself from the business of selling software applications so
as not to anger independent companies in that business. Ever
since, Mr. Sculley has cited Claris as an example of what he
describes as a "federation" of companies all supporting the
Apple "mothership."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   According to industry executives familiar with the
situation, Apple changed its mind because it believes it
needs more control over software applications for its
computers at a time when some of the most creative
independent software companies are beginning to spend more
resources on producing applications for competitors'
computers.
   Spokesmen for both Apple and Claris declined to comment,
but industry executives said Apple was ready to announce the
move as early as today.
   "It's a very sensible decision in my opinion," said
Charles Wolf, an analyst at First Boston Corp. "The entire
premise for setting up Claris no longer holds."
   Mr. Wolf said that unlike several years ago, when Apple's
flagship Macintosh computer had an insufficient amount of
software, there is plenty available for the machine today.
Apple now faces a situation where the outside firms that
write software for the Macintosh have been so successful that
they have begun writing software for machines based on
arch-rival International Business Machines Corp.'s personal
computers.
   Indeed, even executives at Claris conceded that once the
firm was independent from Apple, which was scheduled to
happen later this year, it too would begin writing software
for personal computers made by Apple competitors. While
Claris has posted yearly revenue about $100 million from
selling software from Apple computers, investment bankers,
handling the subsidiary's stock offering, insisted that
Claris broaden its business to flourish outside of Apple's
umbrella.
   According to people familiar with the situation, Michael
Spindler, who was named Apple's chief operating officer in
January, would not brook such a situation. He is said to
believe that Apple must have some internal capacity to
produce applications software that takes advantage of what
the company considers the unique features of its Macintosh
computers.
   Bringing Claris, which is the second biggest supplier of
Apple software after Microsoft Corp., back into Apple could
upset some independent software developers who are wary about
competing directly with Apple in software applications. But
the benefits of an internal applications business are worth
the criticisms.
   "Now Apple has a currency to retain the unique software on
the Macintosh," Mr. Wolf said.
   The flip-flop on the status of Claris is only one of many
organizational and strategic changes occurring at the
Cupertino, Calif., computer maker. This week, the company
hired a new president of Apple USA, its biggest sales and
marketing organization and yesterday it announced the
departure of one of its most senior executives in product
development.
   Donald P. Casey, Apple's vice president of networking and
engineering, joined Lotus Development Corp., a Boston-based
software company, as its new vice president of the
spreadsheet division, in charge of its key revenue source.
   Mr. Casey, 44 years old, said that the Lotus job "is a
great opportunity." He said he wasn't leaving Apple in a
dispute over strategy, but declined to comment on Apple's
outlook.
   Most of the changes are related to decisions made by Mr.
Spindler, who ran Apple's fast-growing European operations
before coming to headquarters to revive the company's
domestic marketing and streamline its field organization.
   On the product side, meanwhile, Apple also has made an
about-face. In recent years the company has introduced a
series of increasingly expensive computers. While successful,
these products have sharply narrowed the market for Apple's
machines, leading analysts to complain that the company is no
longer catering to the mass market.
   Mr. Sculley has made it plain that he intends to fix that
and since taking over direct responsibility for Apple's
product development in late January has been spending most of
his time trying to rush into creation two lower-priced
Macintosh machines.
   While outsiders question the wisdom of Mr. Sculley's
direct involvement in product planning -- the Apple chief is
a marketing man and has no formal training in engineering --
executives inside Apple's product development groups say he
is getting results.
   "Apple's playing a different game now, and frankly, that's
very refreshing," said Lawrence Tesler, vice president for
advanced products at Apple. Mr. Tesler approves of Mr.
Sculley's emphasis on less-expensive models because he
believes it will result in a broader following among computer
users.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900629-0156
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900629-0156.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Notable &amp; Quotable
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<LP>
   Princeton economist William Baumol at a Manhattan
Institute seminar on May 14:
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   I see nothing frightening about foreign direct investment
in America. As a matter of fact, almost every country during
its period of takeoff has had plenty of investment from
abroad, in the form of foreigners buying plants and taking
over businesses. Historically, if you go back as far as the
middle ages, there were in succession three clear leaders
before the United States: Italy, Holland, and Great Britain.
In the century before Italy lost its leadership,
opportunities for investment in Italy didn't look too good
and so the Italian bankers sent their money abroad. No one
was spending money in Italy. They lent it to the King of
Spain (who would eventually go bankrupt) and to the King of
England and other useful enterprises like that. When the
Dutch took over, in the century before their decline, people
stopped investing in Holland, including the Dutch, and
started to invest in England, because a country in decline is
not a good place to invest in. Then when the British reached
what is called their apex, they also started to send their
capital abroad. In 1913, half of British savings were
exported. So it is certainly not a sign of decline if the
rest of the world is willing to send money to the United
States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900629-0155
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900629-0155.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Money Fund Assets
   Fell $444.9 Million
   In the Latest Week
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C23
</SO>
<IN>
MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Assets of the nation's 513 money market funds
fell $444.9 million to $384.99 billion in the week ended
Wednesday, according to the Investment Company Institute, a
Washington-based trade association.
   While assets of 250 general purpose funds rose $27.7
million to $133.99 billion, assets of 102 broker-dealer funds
declined $356.4 million to $159.17 billion. Assets of 161
institutional funds dropped $116.2 million to $91.83 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The number of money market funds was revised from 512 the
previous week to include one new general purpose fund with
assets of $112.5 million. For the week ended June 20, money
market fund assets were revised to $385.43 billion and the
reported increase of $1.29 billion in the week was revised to
$1.32 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
