<HL>
   Manufacturers
   Hanover Sets
   Sizable Charge
   ----
   By Douglas R. Sease
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   MHC X.TMP CCI BT CMB MIDL FFB
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Manufacturers Hanover Corp. said it will take
a substantial charge against second-quarter earnings as a
result of the bank holding company's cost-cutting
reorganization plan.
   The company also said that it will place more than $150
million in loans to developer Donald Trump on nonperforming
status. Other lenders are expected to take similar action in
reclassifying a portion of their loans to Mr. Trump as
nonperforming.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Such status means that the loans aren't performing
according to the original terms of the borrowers' loan
agreement. It doesn't mean the bank won't eventually be
repaid the loans.
   Manufacturers Hanover said that the one-time charge will
reduce operating earnings for the second quarter below the
$96 million, or $1.21 a share, it earned in this year's first
quarter. Although the size of the charge hasn't been
determined, it isn't expected to exceed the bank's operating
earnings for the second quarter.
   The disclosures came in a prospectus for the proposed sale
of four million shares of Manufacturers Hanover preferred.
   Manufacturers stock closed at $34.50, off 25 cents, in New
York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   Like many other large banks, Manufacturers is struggling
to reduce expenses in the face of slack corporate finance
business. It earlier announced a reorganization aimed at
slashing costs to bring them more in line with expected
revenue.
   Chemical Banking Corp., Bankers Trust New York Corp. and
Chase Manhattan Corp. all have taken or face the need to take
similar charges as a result of restructurings, industry
experts say.
   Although Manufacturers' prospectus didn't identify Mr.
Trump specifically, it said its portfolio of nonperforming
loans would increase by about 15% in the second quarter
"principally because of problems being experienced by one of
the corporation's major real estate customers." A bank
official identified the customer as Mr. Trump.
   Manufacturers' nonperforming loan portfolio, exclusive of
Third World debt, stood at $1.04 billion as of March 31.
   Bank industry sources said Mr. Trump's other major bank
lenders -- Citicorp, Bankers Trust and Chase -- would almost
certainly place the portion of their loans to Mr. Trump on
which interest payments have been deferred on nonperforming
status as well. Under a tentative agreement between Mr. Trump
and the banks this week, interest payments on some $850
million of loans have been deferred in exchange for an
additional five-year, $65 million loan that will enable Mr.
Trump to avoid defaults on debt agreements.
   A spokesman for Chase said that some portion of the bank's
loans to Mr. Trump would be placed on nonperforming status,
but not loans on which Mr. Trump continues to make interest
payments. Other banks refused to comment on their treatment
of the Trump loans.
   Additionally, two New Jersey banks with substantial loans
to Mr. Trump -- First Fidelity Bancorp. and Midlantic Corp.
-- refused to disclose how they're dealing with their loans
to Mr. Trump. However, First Fidelity earlier said it would
set aside as much as $300 million for past-due loans in the
second quarter, a portion of which is believed to be loans to
Mr. Trump.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900629-0120
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900629-0120.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Potomac Watch --
   Russians Urge:
   Please Don't Help
   Our Government
   ----
   By Paul A. Gigot
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   MOSCOW -- So the West wants to bail out Mikhail Gorbachev.
Germany and France have proposed a $20 billion subsidy, the
usual suspects are signing on and George Bush has sent up a
trial balloon. But what if the better Russians don't want to
be bailed out by the West?
   Wandering around this city-that-doesn't-work (Manila on
the Moscow) this week, I put the question of Western aid to a
variety of reformers. Politicians, journalists, economists --
these are the people who want to go beyond Mr. Gorbachev's
inchoate reforms to create private property and democratic
politics. They are the ones who will have to prevail if
Russia ("U.S.S.R." will soon be passe) is ever going to join
the civilized, developed world. Aid for Gorby? Every single
reformer is ambivalent at the very least, and usually
flat-out opposed.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Sometimes I think the worst enemies of democracy in my
country are democrats in the West," says Ilya Zaslavsky, a
member of the reformist Interregional Group of Deputies in
the Soviet parliament. "You are always trying to help our
dictatorship." Mr. Zaslavsky is slight, has hair that is
early-Beatles and like most Russians has a well honed gift
for irony.
   But his view is hardly eccentric. I couldn't find a single
reformer, moderate or radical, who endorsed Western help to
today's Kremlin. The current system is understood as a black
hole.
   ---
   Andrei Anikin, a prominent economist, figures the
government wasted $200 billion during the oil-price boom of
the 1970s. Alexander Bogomolov, a young establishment
economist (his father, Oleg, is an adviser to Boris Yeltsin),
says the Gorbachev regime has already squandered billions in
recent loans from West Germany.
   "In the current structure, aid is useless," says Mr.
Bogomolov. "We have no economic or political mechanisms that
would let us use it effectively." The elder Bogomolov tells
my colleague Peter Gumbel he feels the same way.
   Of course, the more seductive argument is that Western aid
would somehow leverage free-market reform. Some reformers are
willing to try this, though less to assist Mr. Gorbachev than
to twist his arm. Mr. Anikin, despairing of any new Gorbachev
ideas for at least another year, wants the International
Monetary Fund or the United Nations (]) to more or less
dictate reform. Mr. Bogomolov hopes the West will treat
economic reform the way it has arms control -- negotiating
Soviet concessions. Still others agree that the Kremlin is
hopeless, but would welcome aid to the newly democratic local
governments in such cities as Leningrad and Moscow.
   But the difficulties are obvious. Do Americans really want
to take credit for raising prices for bread and rent? This is
also not a banana republic case of selling a few hundred
state enterprises; the entire country is a state enterprise.
The Soviet parliament recently spent three days deciding that
"individual" (though, strangely, not "private") property is
all right, but land must still be owned by the state. As for
aiding cities, it's hard to imagine George Bush or Helmut
Kohl telling Mr. Gorbachev they're going to write checks to
his political rivals in Leningrad.
   A visit with a budding Russian "capitalist" isn't
reassuring, either. Igor Grishenko is blond, only 31 years
old and claims to make 3,500 rubles a month (the Soviet
average is some 240). He runs a Moscow "cooperative," the
only kind of legal private enterprise. But his clients are
state ministries, he had to buy his building from city hall
and he neatly dodges a question about political payoffs. In
any case, even Mr. Grishenko says, "we can do without"
foreign subsidy.
   The reformers' best point is more political than economic,
going to the heart of what they call their 73-year-old
"insanity." Western liberals approach the Soviet Union as
just another repair job: Change the carburetor and spark
plugs and it'll be back on the road again. Reform the
currency to mop up the "ruble overhang" and everyone will be
in business.
   ---
   Russian reformers know better. Over and over again a
visitor hears from reformers that they long to live in a
"normal" society. They know their system now is abnormal,
absurd. It nurtures a culture of bribery. (Anecdote: A
five-minute phone call to the U.S. costs $50, but the hotel
operator appears in a guest's room at 5 a.m. to say it will
cost only $25 -- if you pay her then in greenbacks.) Theft is
encouraged; work is punished.
   As Yuri Shekochikhin, another reformer in the parliament,
puts it: "We have two economies -- a corrupt official one,
and a quick, efficient one that's illegal. Why don't we
legalize the black one?" He answers his own question: Because
the corrupt system exists to sustain the power of the
communist "nomenklatura". The Party still owns 95% of the
means of production. "We must change this oligarchical
system," adds Mr. Zaslavsky. "This one knows how to eat, but
not how to produce." Foreign aid in this system will do
little more than increase the velocity of the bribes.
   It's probably true that this is exactly what the Germans
intend, and they don't much care. Chancellor Kohl wants to
pay a ransom for German unification and to keep Gorby from
meddling in German elections later this year. The "dirigiste"
French also like ideas that enhance their international
influence while spending other people's money. But the U.S.
has other priorities. George Bush once said he didn't want to
jeopardize Soviet reform by "doing dumb things -- that's my
cautious approach." Here's his chance to prove it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900629-0119
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900629-0119.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Insurers to Form
   Computer Network
   For Linking Agents
   ----
   By Beatrice E. Garcia
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   FFC TIC AIG CNA LTR
</CO>
<IN>
INSURANCE (INS)
SOFTWARE (SOF)
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   A group of insurers and two data-management companies
formed a venture to provide a computer network designed to
expedite the processing of policies and the flow of pricing
information to independent agents.
   The venture, known as Alliance for Productive Technology,
hopes to create a standardized software system to let
insurance agents transmit and retrieve information from
several companies without having to re-enter policyholder
data several times.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But consumer groups and insurance-industry critics
expressed skepticism about the likely benefits of the planned
system. Moreover, the approach excludes the direct insurance
writers, companies such as State Farm Mutual Automobile
Insurance Co., Nationwide Insurance Co. and Allstate
Insurance Co., a unit of Sears, Roebuck &amp; Co., that have
their own sales personnel, rather than working through
independent agents around the country.
   Industry studies have found that these companies are
already more efficient than the agency companies and offer
generally better pricing to consumers.
   Participating in the network venture are CNA Insurance
Cos., Fund America Cos.' Fireman's Fund Insurance unit,
Travelers Corp. and New Hampshire Insurance Co., a unit of
American International Group Inc. They will provide some of
the capital to develop the software link that agents and
companies will be using.
   The aim is to make both the agents and the insurers more
efficient. Automation in the insurance industry remains
fragmented, and no standard for linking companies and agents
exists.
   Agents need to be more productive, said Thomas Eustace,
chairman and chief executive officer of Applied Systems Inc.,
one of the data-management companies involved in the project.
He acknowledged that efficiencies envisioned by this software
system will be achieved only if many companies use it. The
other data-management firm is Agency Management Systems Inc.,
a Norwell, Mass.-based firm that is jointly owned by CNA,
Fireman's Fund and New Hampshire Insurance.
   Robert Hunter, head of the National Insurance Consumers
Organization, said the need to develop such systems is "an
admission that there are some fairly large inefficiencies" in
insurance company operations.
   He said he agrees that companies could achieve significant
savings if their back offices didn't have to re-enter
information they get from agents several times, such as
pricing, billing and claims processing. However, consumers
may not see any immediate benefit from this computer link, he
said.
   Unlike the airline reservation systems, which gives
consumers with a personal computer access to airfare listings
and schedules, this system won't be available to the public.
Consumers will still have to rely on agents to get pricing
information.
   "If the consumer isn't given good pricing information,
then (this system won't) do the consumer any good," said Mark
Cooper, an economist with the Consumer Federation of America.
   A variety of data management companies already provide
computers and software to automate insurance agents' offices.
But some of these systems are incompatible and they force
agents to re-enter the same data for such operations as
accounting and pricing. Also, many of the major insurers, who
work through independent agents, have developed their own
systems for their agents to use, often making it
time-consuming and cumbersome for agents to deal with more
than a few companies.
   "Some companies try to compete for agents based on
automation they can offer. They ought to compete on the basis
of price and service," said Patricia A. Borowski, head of
government and industry affairs for the National Association
of Professional Insurance Agents.
   The insurance industry has been trying to establish a
data-communications system between agents and insurance
companies for several years now, but success has been
minimal. "It's not a technology issue," Ms. Borowski said.
"It's a political issue of whether or not (an insurer) wants
to have its agents communicate with multiple companies or
give them a system to communicate with just one company."
   The standardized software being developed by the joint
venture will be marketed to all property-casualty companies.
Lawrence Bacon, senior vice president for data-processing at
Travelers, said the various data-management firms that
specialize in agency automation should be able to incorporate
this software in the various systems they now sell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
