<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   Disorder in the Court
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
</IN>
<GV>
SUPREME COURT (SUP)
</GV>
<LP>
   On Wednesday, the Supreme Court ruled that Arizona's
death-penalty law was constitutional.
   Yesterday, the Supreme Court ruled that Arizona's
death-penalty law was unconstitutional.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   This unprecedented 24-hour-long precedent is new evidence
of how manipulative the liberal minority on the Supreme Court
has become. This term had other rulings that can only serve
to confuse many people about the Constitution's meaning. The
court allowed judges to levy taxes to pay for school
desegregation and let regulators grant broadcast licenses
based on race or gender. But this two-day flip-flop takes the
cake.
   The immediate impact is that the murderer of reporter Don
Bolles will not be executed and that no one knows if the
death penalty in Arizona or similar laws in Idaho and Montana
are constitutional.
   One-day "stare decisis" is the latest outrage from the
high court in death-penalty cases. Since 1976, the court has
ruled in various cases either that there was too much
discretion by a judge or a jury to issue the death sentence
-- or not enough discretion to sentence prisoners instead to
imprisonment.
   Wednesday's ruling in Walton v. Arizona upheld a law that
gave the trial judge discretion to find aggravating
circumstances that justify the death penalty. Jeffrey Walton
had left his robbery victim blinded by a gunshot to the head
in the Arizona desert to die a death of dehydration,
starvation and pneumonia.
   The five justices who upheld the death penalty were Chief
Justice Rehnquist and Justices White, O'Connor, Scalia and
Kennedy. The four dissenters were Justices Brennan, Marshall,
Blackmun and Stevens; Justices Brennan and Marshall repeated
their extralegal view that no death penalty under any
circumstances can be constitutional despite the
Constitution's explicit support for death sentences.
   This 5-4 lineup upholding the death sentence set the stage
for the flip-flop in Lewis v. Adamson the very next day.
Harvey Adamson had been convicted and sent to death row for
the 1976 bomb killing of Mr. Bolles, an investigative
reporter for the Arizona Republic.
   The court's decision to spare Adamson came in a 4-3 vote.
What happened is that only seven justices participated in the
decision whether to review the appeals-court decision that
had invalidated the Arizona law. This was because Justice
O'Connor, a former Arizona judge, and Justice Kennedy, a
former federal appeals judge, had participated in lower-court
decisions in this case. They recused themselves. This allowed
Justices Brennan, Marshall, Blackmun and Stevens to reverse
the previous day's ruling with only three justices available
to disagree with them.
   Whatever you think of the death penalty, this was judicial
dirty pool. The four liberal justices apparently decided it
was worth junking standard judicial procedure in order to
"win" Adamson. When the Supreme Court rules in a related
case, as it did in Walton v. Arizona, the justices typically
follow what is known in court shorthand as G-V-R.
   This stands for granting the petition to review the case,
vacating the lower-court ruling and remanding the case back
to the lower court for reconsideration in light of the new
high-court ruling. The four instead short-circuited this
procedure by declaring the Arizona death penalty dead after
one day.
   Justice Scalia must have known the liberals were about to
pull this stunt when he wrote a separate opinion in
Wednesday's case upholding the death sentence. "A
jurisprudence containing the contradictory commands that
discretion to impose the death penalty must be limited but
discretion not to impose the death penalty must be virtually
unconstrained," he wrote, caused a "permanent flood-tide" of
appeals. This back and forth on the death penalty, he said,
causes "a fundamental uncertainty in the law that shows no
signs of ending or even diminishing."
   Justice Scalia's example of absurd uncertainty in the law
was the lower-court opinion in the Adamson case, which he
noted was "essentially identical" to the Walton case
upholding the death penalty. He knew then what we know now --
that the views of five justices would last only a day when
confronted with the views of four.
   The court ends the term with the liberals perhaps
understandably feeling the pressure of minority status.
Still, there can be no excuse for gamesmanship in
constitutional law. There certainly is no justice when a
murderer gets to escape the ultimate punishment simply
because he had the good fortune that two justices had to
recuse themselves from his case. The likely solution will
come only when President Bush gets the chance to replace some
of the less principled members of this court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900629-0112
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900629-0112.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   You Filled In the Wrong Blank Check
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A13
</SO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   Given your ideological bias, it's only natural your
editorial focused on the wrong blank check in assessing blame
for the S&amp;L mess ("History of a Blank Check," May 24).
Contrary to your editorial, deposit insurance is not the
major culprit.
   The blank check was the Reagan administration's
well-documented disdain for adequate supervision and
regulation of the savings-and-loan industry in the early
1980s. The blank check was product and services deregulation
that outran supervisory capacity, and the failure of the
Reagan administration and Congress to limit the flow of
brokered deposits to crooked and brain-dead S&amp;Ls. Yes,
increasing deposit-insurance coverage to $100,000 upped the
amounts that could be brokered, but this was controllable.
The administration and Congress just chose not to control it,
since deregulation and desupervision were in -- let the free
market roll.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Your solution to the problems confronting the S&amp;L industry
and banking is to cut back existing levels of deposit
insurance. This will only further undermine consumer
confidence in our increasingly fragile financial system and
weaken further our economic and financial system. It would
weaken healthy S&amp;Ls by driving out their depositors, which
would further escalate costs to the taxpayer. And in terms of
international competitiveness, American banks have to offer
the same product offered by their major Japanese and European
competitors. And as Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. Chairman
William Seidman recently testified, what our foreign
competitors offer is that no depositor in a major bank
anywhere in the world has lost a penny since the end of World
War II. Banks are special and they always should be -- their
coin is other people's money.
   Kenneth A. Guenther
   Executive Vice President
   Independent Bankers Association of America
   Washington
   ---
   Bravo] Better late than never.
   You correctly fix the blame for the S&amp;L mess on
deregulating the thrift industry immediately after raising
the deposit insurance to $100,000 per account, for no
apparent reason. Thus the Reagan administration set the stage
for the biggest financial scandal the world has ever seen,
beginning in 1980.
   I applaud you for your mea culpa, acknowledging somewhat
sheepishly, "we ourselves missed the importance of the
$100,000 figure, but by the time of the 1982 bill warned, `As
things stand now, deregulation under guaranteed banking will
give banks a competitive edge in attracting funds from the
public while compounding the opportunity for bank managements
to behave imprudently.'"
   Smart people at the FDIC and in Congress have known for a
long time that the current 100% insurance per deposit invites
disaster. You mention two of the most obvious cures: insuring
only 85% of the insurable limit, or whacking the limit of
insurance in half. I would prefer both.
   A scream would go up that this would discriminate against
$100,000 depositors who had put their money in relying on the
full faith and credit of the federal patsies. There is a
simple way to keep faith with them and still put in place a
system that will make sure it doesn't happen again: Keep the
current deposits insured as they now are, but put the new,
more prudent system in place for all future deposits. After
the law is passed, of course.
   I suppose there would be a flight to quality by
depositors, but in the long run that would go a very long way
to make sure it never happens again.
   Karl L. Monroe
   Retired Editor/Publisher
   The Collinsville Herald
   Collinsville, Ill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
