<HL>
   International:
   Venezuela Reaches
   Debt Settlement
   With Major Banks
   ----
   By Peter Truell
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Venezuela and its major bank creditors
agreed on a debt settlement that includes provisions for new
loans and for cutting back old credits and interest payments
due on them.
   The settlement, which covers an estimated $20 billion of
medium-term and long-term foreign commercial bank debt, is
weighted more toward providing the country with new credits
than a recent similar bank-debt settlement with Mexico, the
first under the revamped U.S. debt strategy.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The agreement will be explained to Venezuela's smaller
bank creditors at meetings to be held in international
financial centers over the next several weeks.
   Under the agreement, negotiated in New York over the past
few months, the country's bank creditors will have four
options.
   First, to help provide Venezuela with new credits, banks
can purchase Venezuelan bonds to be issued over the next two
years. If they purchase these new money bonds, banks, as a
sweetener, will be able to exchange old loans for
debt-conversion bonds at a ratio of five such bonds for each
new money bond they buy. Banks often prefer to hold bonds
rather than loans because they are more easily traded.
Moreover, these conversion bonds will be eligible to be
exchanged for equity investments in Venezuela.
   The second option will allow bank creditors to exchange
their old loans for short-term collateralized notes at a 55%
discount. These 91-day notes will be collateralized by U.S.
Treasury bills. But if they use this option, banks will
receive only 45 cents for each dollar face value of debt, a
rate roughly equal to the secondary-market price for
Venezuelan government foreign-bank debt. The Venezuelans will
accept as much as $5.5 billion of loans under this option.
   The third option will allow banks to exchange loans for
30-year bonds that have their principal fully secured at
maturity by zero-coupon bonds. These new bonds either carry
fixed interest rates of 6.75% or represent a 30% discount to
the face value of the loan tendered.
   The fourth option will allow banks to swap credits for
17-year bonds that have below-market interest rates for the
first five years of their life. These bonds will be backed by
a fund that guarantees 12 months of interest payments for
their first five years of life.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900629-0081
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900629-0081.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Ionics Inc. Expects
   Profit to Rise 30%
   In Second Quarter
   ----
   By Lawrence Ingrassia
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6G
</SO>
<CO>
   ION
</CO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
</IN>
<LP>
   WATERTOWN, Mass. -- Ionics Inc., benefiting from growing
concern about water-quality issues, is comfortable with
analysts' estimates of second-quarter earnings and sales
gains, Arthur L. Goldstein, chairman and chief executive
officer, said.
   The company, while not making a specific forecast, doesn't
quarrel with estimates of about 26 cents a share in the
second quarter, a rise of 30% from the 1989 period's net
income of $839,000, or 20 cents a share, Mr. Goldstein said
in an interview.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Ionics, which makes purification systems, expects revenue
to grow "15% or a little better" from the year-earlier
period's $26 million, he said.
   Most of Ionics' businesses are posting healthy revenue
gains, but its Aqua Cool bottled water business is showing
particularly sharp growth. With revenue expected to increase
25% to 30% in the second quarter and year, Aqua Cool now
provides nearly 10% of Ionic's revenue, Mr. Goldstein said.
   Aqua Cool is purified drinking water sold mostly in
five-gallon containers for coolers in offices but also in
smaller containers in supermarkets. Originally introduced
overseas, Aqua Cool is expanding steadily in the eastern
U.S., with the newest markets being Stamford, Conn., New York
City and northern New Jersey.
   Ionics believes it is among the 20 largest companies in
the fast-growing, highly fragmented bottled-water market and
expects to improve its position as it moves toward national
distribution. "Our goal is to become a major player in this
market. . . . We hope to be in the top 10 to 15 companies in
the next couple of years," Mr. Goldstein said.
   The executive said it will be easier for Ionics to expand
geographically than for some of its competitors because
Ionics can "manufacture" Aqua Cool water anywhere with its
purification system. Thus, it won't have to transport bottled
spring water long distances or buy regional companies.
   Ionics has introduced a cooler that can dispense seltzer
water by adding carbonation. While that business is only
starting to become profitable, "by the end of this year it
will become an important profit contributor," Mr. Goldstein
said.
   Ionics also is experiencing strong growth with its
water-purification systems for companies in the
power-generating, electronics and pharmaceutical industries,
Mr. Goldstein said. This water is used in power-plant
boilers, in pharmaceutical fluids and to clean computer
chips, among other things. Demand is growing because use of
less pure water can lower operating efficiency and increase
maintenance costs, he said.
   Ionics, which also makes desalination systems, said
contracts for major systems contributed to its second-quarter
earnings and sales gains. The company's backlog, which
consists mostly of large desalination and purification
systems, is about the same as the record backlog of $64.5
million at the end of the first quarter.
   For the year, Mr. Goldstein said he isn't "uncomfortable"
with analysts' estimates of earnings of $1.10 to $1.15 a
share, or 30% to 35% higher than last year's $3.6 million, or
85 cents a share. Revenue is expected to rise at least 15%
from last year's $108.9 million, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900629-0080
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900629-0080.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Positives Aplenty Seen in Quarter's Profits
   ----
   By Douglas R. Sease and Christopher Winans
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Despite scattered earnings disappointments,
such as the announcements earlier this week by American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. and Caterpillar Inc., the overall
outlook for second-quarter profits holds more hope than
horror.
   AT&amp;T and Caterpillar shocked investors by disclosing that
earnings aren't meeting expectations. AT&amp;T said Wednesday
that its second-quarter profit probably will be below
year-earlier results, while Caterpillar said Monday that it
expects current-year earnings will be "substantially lower"
than last year's.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But analysts and money managers say there is little
evidence of earnings problems at many other large companies.
Indeed, they are counting on seeing plenty of pleasant
surprises in coming weeks, as corporations report their
second-quarter results.
   This is good news for investors who have a broadly
diversified portfolio of stocks. The flood of second-quarter
earnings reports to be released in the next few weeks isn't
likely to wash the value of these investors' shares down the
drain.
   At the same time, however, investors who are heavily
committed to a single stock that dares to disappoint Wall
Street with worse-than-expected results had better brace
themselves. They're apt to get hammered.
   That's the lesson analysts and money managers find in the
seemingly paradoxical performance of the Dow Jones Industrial
Average and AT&amp;T, a key component of the industrial average,
following Wednesday's announcement. That day, irritated
investors dumped AT&amp;T shares, driving the price down $2.125,
to $39.125, on volume of 11.5 million shares. AT&amp;T's normal
daily volume is 1.8 million shares. Yet even as AT&amp;T plunged
Wednesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average surged up 19.80
points to close at 2862.13 in light trading. Yesterday,
turnover of more than 3.7 million shares of AT&amp;T made it the
most active Big Board issue for the second consecutive
session, and the shares lost 37.5 cents, to finish at $38.75,
as the industrial average rose 16.58 points to 2878.71.
   Investors also punished Caterpillar on Monday, driving the
price down $5 a share to $58.50 on the Big Board, following
the company's earnings announcement. On Tuesday, the slide
continued, as Caterpillar shares fell $6. Then the stock
stabilized, and closed yesterday at $52.375, up 12.5 cents.
   Not everyone believes that such incidents will be the
exception. Abby Joseph Cohen, a market strategist at Barclays
de Zoete Wedd, the securities unit of Barclays Bank, says all
the earnings optimism scares her.
   Through the first quarter, she says, earnings of the S&amp;P
500 stocks amounted to $21.67 a share. For all of 1990, she
estimates earnings of the group at $22 a share, down from
$22.88 last year. "What that means is that sometime beginning
right about now and accelerating through the fall, there's
going to be an overwhelming number of earnings-estimate
revisions on the downside."
   But Ms. Cohen is clearly in the minority. The consensus
expectation among analysts calls for a 10% gain in per-share
earnings for the S&amp;P 500 to about $25.25, says Benjamin
Zacks, executive vice president of Chicago-based Zacks
Investment Research. He calls negative surprises such as AT&amp;T
and Caterpillar "isolated hand grenades."
   And John Bogle, a portfolio manager at Boston-based State
Street Bank &amp; Trust Co., contends, "We haven't seen any
dramatic shift across the entire universe" of about 1,100
stocks that the firm follows.
   At Lynch, Jones &amp; Ryan, a brokerage firm for institutions
that tracks analysts' expectations, Richard Pucci says
estimates for 1990 S&amp;P-500 earnings "bottomed out" earlier
this year. May and June have seen rises in estimates to about
$27.10 a share. "The momentum is toward improved earnings,"
he argues.
   What makes negative earnings surprises so troubling is
that they are usually announced before companies with good
news start making headlines, says Michael Sherman, chief
investment strategist at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. "Between
now and the beginning of July," he predicts, "we'll see a
number of companies going to the confessional," as they find
that the second quarter wasn't as good as they had expected.
   Then, all the companies that discovered the second quarter
was as good as, if not better than, they had expected will
begin releasing their reports, and investors will get "some
very pleasant surprises," he says. He is especially counting
on healthcare, food and technology companies to bring home
the bacon for shareholders.
   Even if investors are disappointed by a company's results,
Mr. Sherman says it is a mistake to sell in a knee-jerk
reaction. "I'm frankly amazed people can sell Telephone
{AT&amp;T} on a bad quarter when the company says it can make it
up the rest of the year," he says.
   And while investors' ire about Caterpillar is easier to
understand -- investors are running out of patience with the
company's long-term turnaround strategy -- reacting too
quickly can be a mistake. "You might decide, based on the
latest news, whether you want to be in it six months from
now, but you wouldn't want to sell on the news," Mr. Sherman
counsels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
