<DOCNO>
WSJ900629-0076
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900629-0076.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   July Economic Summit
   To Consider Soviet Aid
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST EUROP CANDA JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- President Bush and other Western leaders
will discuss at their economic summit in Houston July 9-11
whether to provide aid and loans to the Soviet Union,
according to the Treasury's undersecretary for international
affairs, David Mulford.
   U.S. policy on the issue is still "under review," Mr.
Mulford said. France and West Germany recently have pushed
for more aid for the Soviet Union, but it's widely expected
that discussions at Houston merely will lead to an agreement
to study the issue further.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The U.S., Britain, Canada and Japan want to see more
market-oriented reform in the Soviet Union before committing
large sums of money.
   Mr. Mulford said the leaders of the seven summit countries
-- the U.S., Japan, West Germany, France, Britain, Italy and
Canada -- also will review the state of the international
economy. The Treasury expects the economies of the seven
countries to grow 3% a year in 1990 and 1991.
   The current Uruguay round of trade negotiations under the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade also will be a major
topic at Houston, said Mr. Mulford, who added that he expects
there will be discussion of an impasse over how to address
agricultural subsidies. International debt strategy and
initiatives on the environment, drug trafficking and money
laundering also will be summit items, Mr. Mulford said. He
added that relations with China will be discussed as well.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900629-0075
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900629-0075.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Rostenkowski Introduces
   `Enterprise Zones' Measure
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- House Ways and Means Chairman Dan
Rostenkowski introduced legislation that would create tax
incentives to spur business development in 25 economically
depressed areas.
   The proposal gives new life to the Bush administration's
proposal to create such "enterprise zones," and it represents
a reversal in Mr. Rostenkowski's longstanding opposition to
the idea. Ways and Means Committee staff said the Illinois
Democrat is likely to push the plan, which would cost $1.5
billion over five years, during the White House-congressional
budget negotiations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Both Mr. Rostenkowski's bill and the White House proposal
would offer tax incentives to promote employment and
investment, but there are differences.
   Mr. Rostenkowski would offer small businesses, those with
100 employees or less, that settle in the zones a tax credit
equal to 10% of both the wages paid to employees earning less
than $30,000 and the cost of providing health insurance.
   The White House wants to give a 5% tax credit to
individual workers on their first $10,500 earned. The credit
would be phased at higher wage levels.
   Mr. Rostenkowski's bill would provide for child care,
housing and health insurance in economically depressed zones.
The administration's bill has no such provisions.
</TEXT>
