<HL>
   GM's Pontiac Unit
   Recalls Entire Line
   Of Troubled Fieros
   ----
   By Gregory A. Patterson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   GM
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   PONTIAC, Mich. -- General Motors Corp's. Pontiac division
is widening a recall of the troubled Fiero to include all
these sporty cars that GM ever built.
   The recall, which initially covered 244,000 Fieros
equipped with four-cylinder engines, now includes all the
six-cylinder models, boosting to 308,000 the total units
affected.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The recall is the second for the troubled subcompacts,
which GM stopped building in 1988. In 1987, GM recalled all
1984-model Fieros with four-cylinder engines, because of
defects that have caused engine fires and injuries.
   As part of the latest action, Pontiac said it is offering
a special $750 cash rebate to Fiero owners who purchase
another new Pontiac model by year end.
   GM wouldn't disclose how much the rebate will cost.
   The Pontiac spokesman said the division hasn't considered
extending the special $750 rebate past year end or making it
an outright grant. "We're acknowledging the car has been a
problem, but we still want to keep (owners) in the Pontiac
family," he said.
   GM will begin notifying owners of the recall next week.
But because of the complexity of the repairs and the number
of cars involved, GM is stretching out the notification
period until October. Any owner of a Fiero with problems such
as a smoking engine or engine-related vibrations should take
the car to a dealer now, the Pontiac spokesman said.
   GM wouldn't disclose how much the recall will cost.
   In January, the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration said GM agreed to a second recall because
incidents of Fiero engine fires were continuing, despite
earlier repairs. It wasn't known then that Fieros with
six-cylinder engines would be included in the recall, and GM
didn't explain how it planned to fix the problem.
   When GM began building the Fiero in 1983, the plastic-body
two-seater was hailed as a manufacturing and technological
breakthrough for GM, and sales were strong.
   But engine fires caused by oil leaks ultimately became a
persistent problem for the cars, largely because of the
engine's design. In the first recall, GM adapted the engine,
but in January, the safety agency said this didn't
"completely" eliminate engine fires. GM said yesterday it has
been told of 1,451 fires related to these problems.
   GM agreed to the second recall after negotiating for
months with agency officials. "This is one of the more
complex and extensive fixes, and one of the more extensive
problems, as well," said Michael Brownlee, director of the
federal highway safety agency's defect-investigation office.
The propensity of the Fiero engine to catch afire has been
under investigation by the agency for more than three years.
   GM will make its latest attempt to fix the cars by
installing several new parts, including a new manifold on
older models, and a sheet-metal shield over the manifold on
all models. Dealers also will check Fiero engines, including
the cooling system. Any parts damaged by problems related to
engine fires will be replaced for free, GM said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900629-0052
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900629-0052.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   House Approves
   More Domestic,
   Science Outlays
   ---
   Bill for $83.6 Billion in 1991
   Would Curb Allocations
   For Mars Exploration
   ----
   By David Rogers
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   BEC
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The House approved an $83.6 billion
appropriations bill that would increase spending for major
domestic and science programs by $12.3 billion in fiscal 1991
and restructure President Bush's space budget by cutting
funds for exploration of Mars.
   The final 355-48 roll call came after the chamber rejected
successive efforts to pare back costs across-the-board.
Despite Bush administration protests at the increased
spending, 46 Republicans joined the Appropriations Committee
leadership in rejecting a 2% cut by a 235-172 margin.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Veterans, housing, and environmental programs account for
the bulk of the domestic spending increases, but the measure
taps into a cross-section of liberal and conservative
interests because of the public investment in space and
science.
   National Science Foundation research funding would grow
almost 9% to $1.85 billion, while almost $14.3 billion is
allocated to the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration, a 17% increase from the current year and
almost two-thirds more than was spent in fiscal 1988.
   However large, the proposed NASA budget is $828.8 million
less than the administration's request, and more than $300
million associated with the president's Moon and Mars
initiative would be eliminated entirely. Funding for the
space station and high-speed space plane is preserved --
though below the administration request -- and the House
endorsed a pattern of more generous funding for the ambitious
Earth-observing system, or EOS, to study climate and
atmospheric ozone.
   An estimated $108 million in new funding would be provided
for the EOS instrument program, and another $35 million is
allocated to the continuing total ozone mapping spectrometer,
whose principal contractor is Beckman Instruments Inc. in
California.
   The emphasis on the EOS reflects the priorities of New
York Rep. Bill Green, the longtime ranking Republican on the
appropriations subcommittee that oversees NASA. But a second
factor helping the EOS is that the Jet Propulsion Laboratory
at the California Institute of Technology stands to benefit
from the House decision to add $10 million for work on
synthetic aperture radar. That radar is to measure terrain
and give a more complete picture of global temperature
changes.
   Amid the new money for NASA, little was said of the
discovery this week of flaws in the Hubble Space Telescope,
but the history of the multibillion-dollar instrument is sure
to haunt the administration's efforts to resurrect its Mars
initiative.
   As the senior Republican on the committee, Mr. Green has
stressed NASA's immediate priorities of addressing problems
in the ongoing shuttle and space station programs, and
younger conservatives were frustrated in their efforts to
focus attention on what they see as a high-profile initiative
to give an orientation to their party in the future.
   "I think it's in real trouble," Rep. Robert Walker, the
GOP deputy whip and a member of the House Science, Space, and
Technology Committee, said of the Mars initiative. "We could
very well end up with nothing."
   The Pennsylvania conservative blamed NASA for not
supporting the Mars project more aggressively, but he watched
with evident dismay as members of his own party ridiculed and
killed a relatively modest $6 million appropriation to
continue a decade-long program using radio telescopes to
listen for signs of extraterrestrial intelligence.
   The administration had sought more than $12 million for
the project, which involves the Arecibo Observatory in Puerto
Rico as well as a network of telescopes around the world.
These ambitious plans may well have been its undoing, as more
members saw a vulnerable target to make themselves look tough
on spending.
   The net spending increase of $12.3 billion in the bill
understates the true growth in discretionary appropriations
for the same accounts, but almost half of these funds can be
attributed to required adjustments in existing housing
programs. Thousands of 15-year leases under the so-called
Section 8 housing program for low-income families are coming
due in the next few years, and though the annual expenditures
won't change so drastically, huge appropriations are required
up front to simply renew the existing contracts with
landlords.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900629-0051
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900629-0051.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Moore Asks to Withdraw
   Guilty Plea on 5 Felonies
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9
</SO>
<LP>
   CHARLESTON, W.Va. -- Former West Virginia Gov. Arch A.
Moore Jr. is seeking permission to withdraw his guilty plea
on five felonies relating to a scheme to extort money from a
coal operator and to buy votes.
   In a federal court filing, attorneys for the three-term
Republican governor maintain that his plea was "the result of
a hasty decision forced by a deadline imposed by the
government." The filing seeks permission to plead not guilty.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Moore pled guilty to charges of extortion, fraud, tax
evasion and obstruction of justice. Those charges carried a
maximum 36-year prison sentence and $1.2 million in fines.
   The filing says Mr. Moore was given one day to decide to
plead guilty or face an indictment on 28 counts, including a
federal racketeering charge.
   Moreover, the filing said Mr. Moore was strongly advised
by his counsel, William G. Hundley, to plead guilty after the
government presented Mr. Hundley with recorded tapes relating
to the obstruction charge. The filing said the government
played the tapes and then required a signed plea agreement
within one day to avoid the 28-count indictment.
   Michael Carey, a U.S. attorney, said he would file a
memorandum refuting Mr. Moore's claim and request the court
to proceed with sentencing July 10.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
