<HL>
   Business Brief -- Manatron Inc.:
   Higher Profit to Be Posted
   For Fiscal '90, 4th Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   MANA
</CO>
<LP>
   Manatron Inc., Kalamazoo, Mich., said it will report
operating earnings of $225,000 to $275,000, or 11 cents to 13
cents a share, before the positive impact of its pension-fund
adjustment, for the year ended April 30.
   With the pension-fund adjustment of approximately $250,000
to be recorded in the fourth quarter, Manatron will report
net income of $475,000 to $525,000, or 23 cents to 25 cents a
share, the company said. In its previous year, Manatron had
net of $101,713, or five cents a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   For the fourth quarter, Manatron expects to post operating
earnings of between $75,000 and $125,000, or between four
cents and six cents a share. In the year-earlier quarter,
Manatron had net of $39,119, or two cents a share.
   Allen F. Peat, chairman, said the software and
computer-services company will report earnings in mid-July.
For the nine months ended Jan. 31, Manatron posted net of
$150,465, or seven cents a share, compared with $62,594, or
three cents a share, the year before.
   In a recent interview, Mr. Peat said he expected year-end
revenue of $8.5 million to $8.7 million, compared with $7.7
million in fiscal 1989.
   The higher revenue and earnings result from increased
software sales, Mr. Peat said. Manatron reaped higher
software sales from its movement to expand its personal
computer-based based software and through the service
contracts to maintain the computer systems.
   "As we add new customers, the layer of service revenue
continues to grow," Mr. Peat said, noting that nine of 10 new
customers elect to purchase service contracts as well.
   Manatron's complement of 30 major computer systems that it
markets to governments is mostly complete, Mr. Peat said, and
the company isn't planning to "expend a dramatic effort on
increasing that." he added. Instead, the company will
increase its product offerings on a selective basis, Mr. Peat
said.
   Manatron has customers nationwide, but its core of
customers is in Michigan, Indiana, Illinois and Missouri. The
company's basic customer is a midsized county. Manatron's
computer systems automate functions such as bill collecting
and property deed record keeping.
   Industrywide sales of software to local governments
reaches over $1 billion annually, and there is no
identifiable industry leader, Mr. Peat said. Manatron's
approach has been to develop software for a wide range of
government processing and record keeping functions.
   Manatron hopes to boost sales and earnings 20% annually in
the future, Mr. Peat said.
</TEXT>
