   Los Angeles Firm Reports
   11% Rise in Quarter Profit
</HL>
<DATE>
06/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   TCRD
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Telecredit Inc., which agreed last week to be acquired by
Equifax Inc., posted an 11% rise in fiscal fourth-quarter net
income to $6.6 million, or 59 cents a share, on a small
revenue increase.
   In the same quarter a year ago, Telecredit posted net of
$6 million, or 54 cents a share. Revenue in the quarter ended
April 30 inched up to $38.4 million from $38.2 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Telecredit, based in Los Angeles, guarantees personal
checks for retailers and other merchants and processes credit
cards for credit unions and small and medium-sized financial
institutions.
   Lee A. Ault III, chairman, said the company is "looking
forward to revenue and net earnings gains in the second half
of fiscal 1991 following a relatively flat first half" due to
the loss of a major credit-union customer in October.
   Atlanta-based Equifax, a major provider of credit reports
and similar information for retailers, banks and insurers,
has agreed in principle to acquire Telecredit in a stock swap
valued at about $580 million. Telecredit said it expects a
definitive agreement to be completed by July 10.
